Wei et al. (2022)
1.	What exactly is added to a prompt to make it a chain-of-thought prompt? Reproduce the structure from Figure 1 in your own words.
a.	A chain-of-thought prompt adds intermediate reasoning steps before the final answer instead of asking the model to answer immediately. Rather than jumping straight to a conclusion, the prompt encourages the model to work through the problem one step at a time so each piece of reasoning builds toward the final answer.

2.	Wei et al. report that CoT benefits are "emergent"—they appear only in sufficiently large models. What does this imply for practitioners using smaller or older LLMs?
a.	It suggests that chain-of-thought prompting isn't a magic trick that improves every model. The technique works because larger models have developed reasoning abilities that smaller models simply don't have. If I'm using an older or smaller model, adding CoT instructions may produce longer answers without actually improving the reasoning.

3.	The paper tests CoT on arithmetic, symbolic reasoning, and commonsense reasoning tasks. Which of these task types is most analogous to tasks you perform professionally?
a.	Commonsense reasoning is probably the closest match to my work. Most of what I do involves translating technical information into something useful for students, faculty, or industry partners. That's less about solving math problems and more about organizing ideas, understanding audience, and making good communication decisions.

4.	What is the key limitation of the few-shot CoT approach identified by the authors? Does this concern apply to your planned Task 2 use case?
a.	Few-shot CoT depends on providing good examples in the prompt. If the examples are weak, don't match the task, or take up too much context, the quality can suffer. For my own work, I think this matters because I often write for different audiences. A good example for an academic audience may not work well for industry partners or undergraduate students. I also tend to need things that require waaaay too much context to even start, due to the niche nature of my work, so the Few-shot CoT examples don’t work well without detailed background first.
Word	Definition
Chain-of-thought prompting	A prompting technique that asks the model to work through its reasoning before giving the final answer.
Zero-shot prompting	Giving the AI a task without providing examples of what a good answer looks like.
Few-shot prompting	Giving the AI one or more examples before asking it to complete the task.
Reasoning chain	The sequence of steps the model follows between the question and the answer.

Emergent ability	A capability that only starts appearing once a model becomes large enough, rather than improving gradually as the model grows.

Ji et al. (2023)
1.	How does Ji et al. formally define hallucination in NLG? What is the relationship between "faithfulness" and "factuality" in their framework?
a.	The authors define hallucination as generated content that is either unsupported by the source material or factually incorrect. They distinguish between being faithful to the provided source and being factually correct in the real world. A response can be faithful to a source that itself contains inaccurate information, or it can introduce facts that are true but not supported by the original source.
2.	What is the difference between intrinsic and extrinsic hallucination? Give one example of each that could occur in an academic professional document.
a.	An intrinsic hallucination contradicts the information that was provided. An extrinsic hallucination introduces information that isn't supported by the source at all.  
For example, if I asked AI to summarize a research paper and it changed one of the reported findings, that would be intrinsic. If it invented an additional experiment or citation that wasn't in the paper, that would be extrinsic.
3.	The paper identifies several causes of hallucination in the training process. Which cause do you think is hardest to mitigate through prompt engineering alone?
a.	I think incomplete or inaccurate training knowledge is the hardest to overcome. Prompt engineering can make a model more careful or encourage it to explain its reasoning, but it can't give the model knowledge it never learned or correct incorrect patterns in the training data.
4.	Based on the taxonomy in Section 2, what type of hallucination would you most need to guard against in the professional tasks you identified in your Module 1 reflection?
a.	Extrinsic hallucinations concern me the most because I often write emails, program materials, summaries, and educational resources. A confidently invented citation, statistic, or policy could easily make its way into something I send to students or faculty if I don't verify it.
Word	Definition
Hallucination	Information generated by an AI that is unsupported, made-up, or incorrect.
Intrinsic Hallucination	Something that directly contradicts the information the AI was given.
Extrinsic Hallucination	Something the AI invents that is not supported by the available information.
Faithfulness	How accurately the AI response reflects the source material it was based on.
Factual Grounding	Whether the information in the response is supported by real-world evidence or reliable sources.

 
 
